incident_details: Data Compromised: Email addresses, encrypted passwords (using Secure Remote Password protocol), answers to personal security questions, and Mobile/Dial-In Authenticator information. No financial information, credit cards, billing addresses, or real names were reported compromised.

Data Compromised: Full employee names, corporate email addresses, phone numbers, job titles, office locations, work addresses, and salary information. The company maintained that no sensitive employee data, game code, or player data was accessed, though this was disputed by security researchers.

The Adobe Hack of 2013 led to multiple legal settlements and security improvements over the next several years. The two main resolutions were a class-action settlement in 2015 and a multistate settlement with state attorneys general in 2016.
Nearly 7.5 million Adobe Creative Cloud user records were left exposed to anyone with a web browser, including email addresses, account information, and which Adobe products they use.

On October 2, 2013, the Maine Office of the Attorney General reported a data breach involving Adobe Systems Incorp. Details regarding the breach date and number of residents affected are unknown, but the information compromised included names, payment card expiration dates, encrypted payment card numbers, and other information related to customer orders.

incident_details: Two hackers exploited a vulnerability in AT&T's network to steal email addresses of iPad users via brute force attack. This was AT&T's responsibility, not Apple's directly.
Security researcher discovered vulnerability that could allow hackers to steal passwords; Apple released security update.
Names, IDs, email addresses, mailing addresses
Malicious version of Xcode development tool infected 4,000+ apps
Login credentials, private keys, certificates, purchase receipts
Spear phishing attack compromised iCloud login credentials

incident_details: The Maine Office of the Attorney General reported a data breach involving Comcast Cable Communications LLC, which occurred from October 16 to October 19, 2023, due to unauthorized access following a vulnerability in a software product used by Xfinity's provider, Citrix. The breach affected approximately 35,879,455 individuals, potentially exposing usernames, hashed passwords, names, contact information, last four digits of social security numbers, dates of birth, and secret questions and answers. The breach was discovered on December 6, 2023, and notifications were sent on December 18, 2023.

Seven New Hampshire residents were notified as part of the response actions.

Organizations are notifying impacted users about the breach.

incident_details: The Maine Office of the Attorney General reported a data breach involving Frontier Communications Parent, Inc. on June 6, 2024. The breach, discovered on April 14, 2024, occurred due to external unauthorized access (hacking), affecting approximately 751,895 individuals, including 139 Maine residents. The compromised information includes Social Security numbers, and Frontier is offering one year of complimentary credit monitoring and identity theft resolution services through Kroll.

incident_details: On June 11, 2024, the New Hampshire Department of Justice was notified by Frontier Communications Parent, Inc. of a data breach that potentially affected the personal information of 120 New Hampshire residents. The breach was detected on April 14, 2024, involving unauthorized access to internal IT systems, and Frontier has since taken steps to enhance security and notified law enforcement.

The California Office of the Attorney General reported that Frontier Communications Parent, Inc. experienced a data breach on April 13, 2024, with unauthorized access to their IT systems. The incident potentially affected personal information belonging to individuals, although specific types of information were not detailed in the report. Frontier is offering one year of complimentary credit monitoring and identity theft resolution services in response.

incident_details: The New Hampshire Department of Justice reported on October 17, 2016, that Intuit Inc. experienced unauthorized access to the information of two New Hampshire customers due to fraudulent account log-ins on April 12, 2016. Potentially compromised information included names, Social Security numbers, addresses, dates of birth, driver's license numbers, and financial information. Intuit did not believe the breach resulted from a compromise of their own credentials.

The Maryland Office of the Attorney General reported on March 9, 2016, that Intuit Inc. experienced multiple unauthorized access incidents affecting 30 customers in New Hampshire between March 23, 2016, and April 7, 2016. The potentially accessed information included in-process and prior year tax returns which may contain social security numbers, names, addresses, dates of birth, and driver's license numbers. Intuit has notified law enforcement and is offering identity theft restoration and credit monitoring services free of charge for one year.

incident_details: The California Office of the Attorney General reported a data breach involving Yahoo! Inc. on September 22, 2016. A copy of user account information, potentially affecting at least 500 million accounts, was stolen in late 2014 by what Yahoo believes to be a state-sponsored actor. The stolen information may have included names, email addresses, telephone numbers, dates of birth, and hashed passwords, but did not include unprotected passwords, payment card data, or bank account information.

On December 14, 2016, the California Office of the Attorney General reported data security issues concerning Yahoo! Inc. A third party claimed to have Yahoo user data that was stolen in August 2013, affecting over one billion user accounts. The compromised information may have included names, email addresses, phone numbers, and hashed passwords, but not payment card or bank account data.
